ame":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cumbe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Coomer  . Compare   Coomber  .","Altered form of Native American (Lumbee)   Cumbo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coomer","meanings":["English: topographic name denoting someone who lived in a valley, from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>coumbe</i> ‘(spoon-shaped) valley’; see also   Coombe  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Kummer   and Slovenian   Kumer  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de Cumbe was born in 1345, in Brabourne, Kent, England, her father, John de Cumbe III, was 12 and her mother, Mrs. John De Cumbe III, was 12. She married William John Scott in 1370. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1395, in her hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1345–1395":"1345–1395","1355–1413":"1355–1413","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1333–1360":"1333–1360","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","1447":"1447","1413":"1413","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1355":"1355","1395":"1395","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Scotts Hall, Smeeth, Kent, England":"Smeeth, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fi":{"1345–1395":"1345–1395","1355–1413":"1355–1413","1370–1447":"1370–1447","1333–1360":"1333–1360","1333–Female":"1333–Kuollut","1447":"1447","1413":"1413","1345":"1345","1333":"1333","1355":"1355","1395":"1395","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","Scotts Hall, Smeeth, Kent, England":"Smeeth, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brabourne, Kent, England":"Brabourne, Kent, England"},"fr":{"1345–1395":"1345–1395","1355–14